Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korea complaints about Washington's resistance to a "by-phase" denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, its statement is important, since it did not reject unilateral denuclearization without more, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on 12 June in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up his nuclear weapon first.
Washington has also resisted appeals to mitigate international sanctions to North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even objecting to a declaration of war's end," Ri said.
